It's as if the Father has been

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:33.514
cajoled by the Son,
cajoled out of his repetitive

00:35:33.514 --> 00:35:37.448
cyclicality and nudged toward
something like a more linear

00:35:37.448 --> 00:35:39.374
and,
to my taste,

00:35:39.374 --> 00:35:43.829
a more palatable form of human
progress.

00:35:43.829 --> 00:35:48.425
I think we sigh with relief at
the knowledge that all will be

00:35:48.425 --> 00:35:53.267
well again after the Fall.
We have all the earmarks here

00:35:53.267 --> 00:35:56.894
of a narrative,
moving from a beginning,

00:35:56.894 --> 00:36:00.150
through a middle,
toward an end.

00:36:00.150 --> 00:36:03.899
We sigh with relief at the
knowledge that everything is

00:36:03.899 --> 00:36:07.648
going to be okay.But of
course, this relief is only

00:36:07.648 --> 00:36:10.709
momentary.
As soon as the Father has

00:36:10.709 --> 00:36:15.389
agreed to this concession,
as soon as he's promised their

00:36:15.389 --> 00:36:19.050
safe journey back to God,
he adds a condition,

00:36:19.050 --> 00:36:21.690
and this condition appears at
line 203.

00:36:21.690 --> 00:36:25.320
This is near the top of page
263.

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:29.858
He returns to that rhetoric of
repetition and equivalence that

00:36:29.858 --> 00:36:35.757
had marked his earlier speech;
"but yet all is not

00:36:35.757 --> 00:36:39.486
done…":
[W]ell us'd they shall

00:36:39.486 --> 00:36:41.025
attain,
