00:37:21.829 --> 00:37:25.181
"But yet all is not done":
you can almost hear Milton in

00:37:25.181 --> 00:37:28.349
this line catching himself and
realizing that man,

00:37:28.349 --> 00:37:31.835
of course, wasn't redeemed
simply because Adam and Eve were

00:37:31.835 --> 00:37:35.079
repentant, simply because they
said they were sorry.

00:37:35.079 --> 00:37:38.548
It has the same force as that
incredibly startling moment in

00:37:38.548 --> 00:37:40.900
the Nativity Ode when Milton
tells us,

00:37:40.900 --> 00:37:49.199
"But wisest Fate says No,
/ this must not yet be so."

00:37:49.199 --> 00:37:51.785
Although he certainly [laughs]
gives it a shot,

00:37:51.785 --> 00:37:54.875
he can't get away from the
unhappy fact that man was not

00:37:54.875 --> 00:37:58.360
redeemed simply because Adam and
Eve said they were sorry.

00:37:58.360 --> 00:38:01.904
Man was redeemed through the
much more troubling,

00:38:01.904 --> 00:38:06.409
for Milton, mechanism of the
Father's sacrifice of the Son.

00:38:06.409 --> 00:38:10.707
Milton has successfully avoided
finishing his poem about the

00:38:10.707 --> 00:38:13.868
crucifixion, "The Passion,"
the poem called "The

00:38:13.868 --> 00:38:16.070
Passion," when he was a
young man.

00:38:16.070 --> 00:38:19.731
It just went unfinished.
As you read the dialogue in

00:38:19.731 --> 00:38:22.060
heaven in Book Three of
Paradise Lost,

00:38:22.060 --> 00:38:25.721
for a while at least,
it seems that Milton is going

00:38:25.721 --> 00:38:29.855
to be able to evade the entire
question of the sacrifice one

00:38:29.855 --> 00:38:33.709
more time -- but he catches
himself: "But yet all is not

00:38:33.709 --> 00:38:36.705
done."
He forces a consideration of

00:38:36.705 --> 00:38:39.328
the atonement,
of the crucifixion,

00:38:39.328 --> 00:38:43.303
and it's crucial to
understanding exactly how it is

00:38:43.303 --> 00:38:47.118
that Milton here is imagining
the dynamics of the

00:38:47.118 --> 00:38:51.410
redemption.So Milton first
of all has to reject the

00:38:51.410 --> 00:38:56.179
orthodox understanding of the
Christian redemption.

00:38:56.179 --> 00:39:00.269
I'll remind you what that looks
like.

00:39:00.269 --> 00:39:03.194
In the New Testament,
and for a lot of Christian

00:39:03.194 --> 00:39:06.864
theologians, the redemption
seems to work along the lines of

00:39:06.864 --> 00:39:09.539
something like a revenge
sacrifice and,

00:39:09.539 --> 00:39:13.095
as cultural anthropologists
have taught us,

00:39:13.095 --> 00:39:16.820
there is something like a
primitive logic,

00:39:16.820 --> 00:39:20.458
an intensely primitive logic,
at work behind the notion of

00:39:20.458 --> 00:39:23.139
the Christian notion of the
crucifixion.

00:39:23.139 --> 00:39:26.311
One of the Father's sons,
Adam, has died and so the

00:39:26.311 --> 00:39:29.989
Father will avenge that death by
murdering someone else.

00:39:29.989 --> 00:39:32.920
Of course, that means murdering
another son.

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:37.274
This model of redemption is
based on the repetition,

00:39:37.274 --> 00:39:40.690
or a repetition,
of the initial crime,

00:39:40.690 --> 00:39:44.403
and this logic of repetition,
I think, is largely responsible

00:39:44.403 --> 00:39:47.497
for that rhetoric of
repetitiveness that we hear so

00:39:47.497 --> 00:39:51.362
often in the Father's speech.
According to this -- we can

00:39:51.362 --> 00:39:55.142
think of it as a sacrifice
theory of redemption or of the

00:39:55.142 --> 00:39:57.920
atonement,
God chooses to sacrifice his

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:01.924
son since someone is going to
have to be punished for Adam's

00:40:01.924 --> 00:40:05.651
sin.
The logic demands that.But

00:40:05.651 --> 00:40:10.419
Milton, I think,
can imagine no aspect of his

00:40:10.419 --> 00:40:14.157
religion,
no aspect of Christianity,

00:40:14.157 --> 00:40:19.877
more barbaric than the image of
the Father's willing sacrifice

00:40:19.877 --> 00:40:23.132
of his son.
This would be a God truly

00:40:23.132 --> 00:40:25.929
unworthy of Milton's
justification.

00:40:25.929 --> 00:40:28.582
Milton's struggling here,
and there are a few of his

00:40:28.582 --> 00:40:31.755
contemporaries who are doing the
same thing in the seventeenth

00:40:31.755 --> 00:40:34.158
century.
He's struggling to bring

00:40:34.158 --> 00:40:38.383
Christianity in line with
certain standards of rationality

00:40:38.383 --> 00:40:40.458
and, as Dr.
Johnson had said,

00:40:40.458 --> 00:40:44.387
in the rest of the sentence
that I wrote on the board,

00:40:44.387 --> 00:40:48.760
Milton wants to show the
reasonableness of religion;

00:40:48.760 --> 00:40:52.314
and so Milton replaces the
sacrifice model of the

00:40:52.314 --> 00:40:56.239
redemption with something like a
satisfaction model of

00:40:56.239 --> 00:40:59.184
redemption.
According to this way of

00:40:59.184 --> 00:41:02.929
thinking, in Adam's sin,
a debt has been incurred,

00:41:02.929 --> 00:41:07.362
and this debt can be satisfied
by someone else's payment so

00:41:07.362 --> 00:41:12.102
revenge is no longer the motive.
It's something like an economic

00:41:12.102 --> 00:41:15.557
desire simply to balance the
books.There is something

00:41:15.557 --> 00:41:19.260
impersonal about this new way of
imagining the atonement,

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:23.021
and it's here that Milton gives
the notion of the Christian

00:41:23.021 --> 00:41:25.809
redemption its particular
Miltonic twist.

00:41:25.809 --> 00:41:31.340
Milton's Father does not
willingly sacrifice the Son.

00:41:31.340 --> 00:41:34.932
It's magnificent:
he simply asks for a volunteer,

00:41:34.932 --> 00:41:38.300
and the Son out of his goodness
volunteers.

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:42.300
He chooses to make himself
mortal.

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:47.215
It's a perfect example of how
Milton has shifted the emphasis

00:41:47.215 --> 00:41:51.885
away from Christian orthodoxy
and forced the authoritarian

00:41:51.885 --> 00:41:56.637
image of God's sacrifice to
yield to Milton's liberal image

00:41:56.637 --> 00:42:00.569
of a kind of volunteerism or
libertarian image of

00:42:00.569 --> 00:42:04.555
volunteerism.
The Son chooses to humiliate

00:42:04.555 --> 00:42:08.925
himself and subsequently God
chooses to compensate that

00:42:08.925 --> 00:42:12.889
humiliation with the Son's
supreme exaltation.

00:42:12.889 --> 00:42:17.239
You see the extent of this
compensation at line 311 in Book

00:42:17.239 --> 00:42:20.690
Three, page 265 near the bottom
of the page.

